Source 1: Henry Corbin — Avicenna and the Visionary Recital
1. Source identity

Primary source: Henry Corbin, Avicenna and the Visionary Recital, translated by Willard R. Trask, Bollingen Series LXVI, Pantheon Books, 1960. Google Books lists it as 423 pages, published by Pantheon in 1960.

Public access status: A full text is visible on Internet Archive and scanned PDFs circulate online, but the work is explicitly copyrighted 1960 by the Bollingen Foundation.

Use cautious quotation. For Imaginarium, this should be treated mainly as a summation / structural extraction source, not a quote-heavy source.

Text type: Corbinian philosophical commentary + translation + symbolic exegesis.

Extraction mode:
Use extensive summation, chapter mapping, conceptual extraction, and short legally safe excerpts only. The blueprints can cite public previews, tables of contents, and public text locations, but should not import long passages.

2. Why this source comes first

This is the best first post-Corbin source because it bridges:

Corbin → Avicenna → Suhrawardī → Ibn ʿArabī / ʿAṭṭār

It gives the project a precise grammar for the visionary recital: not fantasy, not metaphor only, but a symbolic drama where the soul encounters its angelic guide and learns to read the cosmos as a map of its own exile and return.

The central Imaginarium value is this:

The world becomes readable as a symbolic geography only when the soul meets the Guide.

The source is especially useful for:

Imaginarium theme	What this source gives
Mundus imaginalis	Pre-Corbinian roots of imaginal geography
Daimon / angel	The personal Angel, Active Intelligence, guide
Taʾwīl	Exegesis of the soul, not just text interpretation
Visionary journey	Orient / Occident, exile, return, ascent
Inner cosmology	Spheres, angels, demons, subtle companions
Narrative engine	Recital as initiatory form
3. Master structural reading

The book has two major movements:

Part I — The Cycle of Avicennan Recitals

This is Corbin’s interpretive engine. It explains why Avicenna’s symbolic tales should be read together as a coherent cycle: Hayy ibn Yaqẓān, The Recital of the Bird, and Salāmān and Absāl.

Google Books and Archive tables of contents show the major sections: “Avicennan Cosmos and Visionary Recital,” “Avicennism and Angelology,” “The Recital of Hayy ibn Yaqẓān,” “The Recital of the Bird,” “From Avicenna’s Recital to ʿAṭṭār’s Mystical Epic,” and “The Recital of Salāmān and Absāl.”

Part II — Translation of the Persian Commentary on Hayy ibn Yaqẓān

This is the practical symbolic map: Angel, companions, Orient, Occident, Spring of Life, darkness around the Pole, celestial spheres, demons of the soul, terrestrial angels, King, and final invitation.

