Source 2: Suhrawardī — The Philosophy of Illumination, Hayākil al-Nūr, and the Visionary Recitals
1. Source identity

Primary figure: Shihāb al-Dīn Yaḥyā al-Suhrawardī, 1154–1191, founder of the Illuminationist / Ishrāqī tradition. SEP describes him as trained in Avicennan Peripateticism but later the major founder of an Illuminationist philosophical tradition in the Islamic East.

Core source cluster:

Ḥikmat al-Ishrāq / The Philosophy of Illumination
Best scholarly English edition: John Walbridge and Hossein Ziai, BYU Press, 1999/2000. It is copyrighted, so use mainly structure, short excerpts, and summation. PhilArchive lists the edition details.

Hayākil al-Nūr / The Temples or Shape of Light
Public scans exist, including The Shape of Light, but the Archive copy explicitly says ©1998 Tosun Bayrak / Fons Vitae, all rights reserved.

Use sparingly. A public PDF also circulates through Traditional Hikma.

Persian visionary recitals:
Especially The Red Intellect, The Chant of Gabriel’s Wing, The Treatise of the Birds, A Day Among the Sufis, and On the State of Childhood. Mehdi Amin Razavi’s public text lists these works and provides a useful map of Suhrawardī’s corpus.

Text type: Illuminationist metaphysics + symbolic visionary narrative + angelology + epistemology of direct presence.

Extraction mode:
Mostly extensive summation and architecture, not quote-heavy reproduction. Use public-access versions for structure and limited excerpts, but treat most translations as copyrighted.

2. Why this source comes second

Avicenna gave the Angel-guide and the visionary recital. Suhrawardī takes that seed and turns it into a full metaphysics of light, presence, Orient, exile, and imaginal ascent.

The transition is:

Avicenna: the soul meets the Angel and learns the map.
Suhrawardī: the whole of reality becomes a hierarchy of lights, shadows, presences, and degrees of awakening.

This is the source where “light” becomes ontological. Not metaphor, not decoration: light is the structure of being, knowing, selfhood, and spiritual rank. SEP states that in The Philosophy of Illumination, Suhrawardī develops a metaphysics of divine lights, with light as the central principle structuring ontology and cosmology.

3. Master structural reading

Suhrawardī should not be treated as “a mystic who liked light imagery.” He is building a new mode of knowing.

His system has three linked layers:

Layer 1 — Ontology of light

Reality is graded by light and darkness. The highest principle is the Light of Lights; lower beings are degrees of illumination, shadow, dependence, and orientation. A public summary notes that Suhrawardī teaches an emanationist cosmology where creation flows from the Supreme Light of Lights.

Layer 2 — Knowledge by presence

Knowledge is not only definition, syllogism, or representation. Suhrawardī’s key epistemological move is presential knowledge: direct self-disclosure, knowing by being present to what is known. SEP describes his epistemology as revolving around ḥuḍūrī / presential knowledge, accessed through intuitive apprehension or contemplative vision.

Layer 3 — Visionary recital

The philosophical system is mirrored by symbolic stories: Red Intellect, Gabriel’s Wing, birds, exile, childhood, mountains, cosmic beings. These are not “examples” after the philosophy; they are the imaginal mode of the same doctrine.

