6. Coverage clusters
Cluster A — Light as Being

This is the central essay cluster. Light is not “a symbol for truth”; rather, truth is a mode of luminosity. Being reveals itself by shining. Darkness is not a rival substance but the degree of non-disclosure, obstruction, or distance from source.

Cluster B — Knowledge by Presence

This is the most important philosophical contribution for the Imaginarium system.

Ordinary knowing: concept, representation, definition.
Illuminationist knowing: presence, disclosure, immediate awareness.

This connects directly to active imagination, visionary cognition, and subtle perception.

Cluster C — The Orient of Light

Suhrawardī inherits Avicenna’s Orient but makes it more intense. The Orient becomes the direction of illumination, origin, and angelic source. The Occident becomes exile, opacity, forgetfulness.

Cluster D — Angelology and Light-Hierarchy

Suhrawardī gives a vertical cosmology of lights. This can map onto:

angelic intelligences
governing lights
celestial archetypes
personal guiding light
imaginal order
Cluster E — The Red Intellect

One of the strongest symbolic engines. The intellect appears as a figure, not as an abstraction. This is ideal for Imaginarium because it turns cognition into encounter.

Cluster F — Gabriel’s Wing

Gabriel becomes a mediator between worlds: wing, chant, revelation, descent, ascent. This gives a symbolic model for how higher intelligence communicates through imaginal form.

Cluster G — Childhood / Primordial Seeing

A rare but important cluster: childhood not as sentimentality, but as perception before the world has hardened into fixed adult categories.

