Source 3: Ibn ʿArabī — Fuṣūṣ al-Ḥikam / The Bezels of Wisdom
1. Source identity

Primary source: Muḥyī al-Dīn Ibn ʿArabī, Fuṣūṣ al-Ḥikam, usually translated as The Bezels of Wisdom or The Seals of Wisdom.

Best public companion base: William C. Chittick, “The Imprint of the Bezels of the Wisdom,” a translation of Ibn ʿArabī’s own Naqsh al-Fuṣūṣ, with abridged Jāmī commentary. Chittick says the Fuṣūṣ is widely recognized as the quintessence of Ibn ʿArabī’s writings and one of the major sources of his influence.

Public source links:

Chittick, “The Imprint of the Bezels”: public PDF via Ibn Arabi Society.

Chittick, “The Chapter Headings of the Fuṣūṣ”: public PDF via Ibn Arabi Society.

Public English Fuṣūṣ PDF scans circulate, but copyright/translation status is unclear, so use mostly summary and structure.

Text type: dense metaphysical scripture-commentary; prophetic wisdom cycle; divine-name ontology; imaginal theophany.

Extraction mode:
Use structural summation + chapter-location mapping + short excerpts only. Chittick’s Imprint is the safest working base because it gives Ibn ʿArabī’s own compressed summary of the Fuṣūṣ and is publicly available through the Ibn Arabi Society.

2. Why this source comes third

Avicenna gave the Angel-guide.
Suhrawardī gave the ontology of Light.
Ibn ʿArabī now gives the metaphysics of manifestation.

The shift is:

Avicenna: the soul travels toward the Angel.
Suhrawardī: reality is a hierarchy of lights.
Ibn ʿArabī: every form is a self-disclosure of the Real.

This is where the Imaginarium stops treating the imaginal as “a realm beside the real” and starts treating form itself as the place where the Real discloses, veils, names, and knows itself.

3. Master structural reading

The Fuṣūṣ is built as a sequence of twenty-seven prophetic wisdoms. Each chapter attaches a specific “wisdom” to a prophet: Adam, Seth, Noah, Idrīs, Abraham, Isaac, Ishmael, Jacob, Joseph, Hūd, Ṣāliḥ, Shuʿayb/Jethro, Lot, Ezra, Jesus, Solomon, David, Jonah, Job, John, Zachariah, Elijah, Luqmān, Aaron, Moses, Khālid, and Muḥammad. The Ibn Arabi Society book listings preserve this sequence across their multi-volume commentary edition.

The structure is not biography. Each prophet is a bezel: a setting in which one jewel of divine wisdom is held and refracted.

So the companion should read each chapter as:

Prophetic form
Specific wisdom-name
Divine-name configuration
Mode of manifestation
Human/perceptual consequence
Imaginarium use
