Source 5: Ibn ʿArabī — selected Futūḥāt al-Makkiyya / The Meccan Revelations
1. Source identity

Primary source: Muḥyī al-Dīn Ibn ʿArabī, al-Futūḥāt al-Makkiyya, usually translated as The Meccan Openings or The Meccan Revelations.

Best public companion base: Muhyiddin Ibn Arabi Society pages by James W. Morris, especially “Introduction to The Meccan Revelations,” “How to Study the Futūḥāt,” and “Spiritual Practice and Other Translations.” The Society identifies the Futūḥāt material as translations from Ibn ʿArabī’s vast work by Michel Chodkiewicz, William Chittick, and James Morris.

Core public-access packet: James Morris’s “Spiritual Imagination and the ‘Liminal’ World,” translating/discussing Futūḥāt chapter 63 on the Barzakh, is publicly listed by the Ibn Arabi Society and also available as a PDF through Sufism.ir. Copyright/public-domain caution: The modern English Meccan Revelations volumes are copyrighted selections, so do not use them as a long-quote base. PIR Press describes Volume I as 22 selected chapters from Ibn ʿArabī’s Futūḥāt on Divine Names, spiritual experience, resurrection, and stages on the path to human perfection.

Use structured summation, short excerpts, chapter references, and public article scaffolding.

Text type: encyclopedic mystical summa; spiritual cosmology; practice manual; metaphysics of imagination; stations and unveilings.

Extraction mode:
Use thematic extraction, not linear coverage of the whole text. The Futūḥāt is too vast for a normal companion. Build selected passage packs around imagination, barzakh, dreams, spiritual practice, bodies of light, stations, resurrection imagery, divine names, and realization.

2. Why this source comes fifth

The prior source, Fuṣūṣ al-Ḥikam, gave the compressed metaphysical skeleton: prophetic wisdoms, divine names, and forms of manifestation.

The Futūḥāt gives the lived, sprawling, visionary ecology:

Fuṣūṣ: the jewel-settings of prophetic wisdom.
Futūḥāt: the immense world in which those wisdoms become stations, dreams, bodies, practices, signs, unveilings, errors, and transformed perception.

This source should not be treated as “more Ibn ʿArabī.” It performs a different function: it is not the compact architecture; it is the field manual of realization.

3. Master structural reading

The Futūḥāt is not best approached front-to-back. Morris notes that Ibn ʿArabī’s work has a huge architectonic table of contents, with 560 chapters, and that the elaborate outline precedes the Introduction.

For Imaginarium, treat it as a modular universe:

Cosmic architecture — worlds, barzakh, resurrection, spiritual realities.
Perceptual training — dreams, unveiling, discernment, imagination.
Practice engine — advice to seekers, spiritual disciplines, adab, stations.
Subtle embodiment — body of light, after-death perception, imaginal form.
Divine-human responsiveness — call/response, prayer, inspiration, receptivity.
Pedagogical storytelling — Ibn ʿArabī teaches through incidents, dreams, reports, and sudden reversals.

This source is therefore best used as selected thematic dossiers, not a single essay sequence pretending to cover the whole work.

