Source 6: Rūzbihān Baqlī — Kashf al-Asrār / The Unveiling of Secrets
1. Source identity

Primary source: Rūzbihān Baqlī, Kashf al-Asrār, translated by Carl W. Ernst as The Unveiling of Secrets: Diary of a Sufi Master.

Author: Rūzbihān Baqlī, 1128–1209, Persian Sufi master associated with Shiraz. He is known for visionary autobiography, ecstatic sayings, divine beauty, and dense first-person mystical prose. Public biographical summaries note that he had visionary experiences from childhood, left Fasa as a teenager for a desert retreat, later established a hospice in Shiraz, and died in 1209.

Best public-access base: Carl Ernst’s public page describes The Unveiling of Secrets as a “visionary diary of astonishing intensity,” written by a major figure in Persian Sufism. The Accessing Muslim Lives page gives a short public excerpt and says the work is autobiographical, dominated by visions and spiritual ecstasies or “unveilings.”

Copyright caution: Ernst’s English translation is modern and copyrighted. Use this source mainly through extensive summation, public excerpts, scholarly descriptions, review materials, and short legally safe quotations only. Avoid long extraction.

Text type: visionary autobiography; Sufi diary; rhetoric of sainthood; ecstatic first-person imaginal testimony.

Extraction mode:
Use structured summation and episode mapping. Because the public text is limited, build the companion from:

Ernst’s public description
available public excerpts
library/review metadata
short scholarly summaries
cautious paraphrase of known episodes
cross-reference to Ernst’s Ruzbihan Baqli: Mysticism and the Rhetoric of Sainthood in Persian Sufism
2. Why this source comes sixth

The first five sources built the architecture:

Earlier source	What it gave
Avicenna / Corbin	Angel-guide, soul-exegesis, Orient/Occident
Suhrawardī	Light ontology, presential knowledge, illumination
Ibn ʿArabī’s Fuṣūṣ	Divine names, manifestation, prophetic wisdoms
ʿAṭṭār	Bird-soul typology, excuses, valleys, annihilation
Ibn ʿArabī’s Futūḥāt	Barzakh, dreams, body of light, practice, imaginal ecology

Rūzbihān now adds something different:

Not system, not parable, not symbolic epic — but first-person visionary intensity.

This source is valuable because it shows the imaginal from inside the visionary subject: childhood ecstasies, encounters with God, angels, prophets, saints, beauty, fragrance, luminous forms, overwhelming states, and the self-presentation of sainthood.

3. Master structural reading

Read Kashf al-Asrār as a visionary autobiography of unveiling.

The main question is not:

“What doctrine does Rūzbihān teach?”

but:

“How does a saint narrate the formation of visionary perception?”

The source works through escalating episodes:

Childhood signs — early visions, spiritual sensitivity, pre-doctrinal ecstasy.
Withdrawal and desert formation — the soul exits ordinary social rendering.
Unveilings — visions of God, angels, prophets, saints, lights, beauties.
Ecstatic legitimation — the visionary self is authorized through encounter.
Beauty-theology — divine beauty appears through faces, forms, fragrance, voices, and inner qualities.
Rhetoric of sainthood — the writing does not merely report sanctity; it constructs a saintly voice.

Public summaries support this basic frame: the work is first-person, autobiographical, vision-dominated, and focused on spiritual ecstasies or unveilings.

