Source 7: Najm al-Dīn Kubrā — Adab al-Sulūk and Kubrawī Visionary Light Material
1. Source identity

Primary figure: Najm al-Dīn Kubrā, 1145–1221, founder of the Kubrawiyya order. He is remembered as a major Central Asian Sufi master and as a pioneer of Sufi analysis of dreams, visions, luminous epiphanies, images, and subtle centres.

Core source base:
Najm al-Dīn Kubrā, Adab al-Sulūk ilā Ḥaḍrat Mālik al-Mulūk, translated as Adab al-Suluk: A Treatise on Spiritual Wayfaring. A public English version is available through Al-Islam.org, which describes it as a translation of one of Kubrā’s Arabic treatises on esoteric wayfaring.

Supplementary Kubrawī source cluster:

Fawāʾiḥ al-Jamāl wa-Fawātiḥ al-Jalāl / The Fragrances of Beauty and the Openings of Majesty — important for visionary light phenomenology.
Later Kubrawī colour systems, especially in ʿAlāʾ al-Dawla Simnānī.
Scholarly material on dhikr, colour, synaesthesia, and early Kubrawī vision theory.

Copyright/public-access caution:
Adab al-Sulūk is publicly available online and can be used as the main working base. Other Kubrawī light materials are more scattered; use public summaries, academic articles, public PDFs, and careful paraphrase. Avoid treating later Simnānī colour maps as if they were all already fully present in Kubrā.

Text type: practical wayfaring manual + visionary phenomenology + subtle-body/light tradition.

Extraction mode:
Use Adab al-Sulūk for concrete practice structure. Use Kubrawī light/colour material as a linked phenomenological dossier.

2. Why this source comes seventh

The sequence so far has built:

Earlier source	Core gift
Avicenna / Corbin	Angel-guide and imaginal geography
Suhrawardī	Light ontology
Ibn ʿArabī, Fuṣūṣ	Divine-name manifestation
ʿAṭṭār	Bird-soul typology and initiatory unmaking
Ibn ʿArabī, Futūḥāt	Barzakh, dreams, body of light
Rūzbihān	First-person ecstatic vision and divine beauty

Kubrā now adds the missing practical-phenomenological layer:

What actually happens in the wayfarer’s perception as dhikr, discipline, retreat, and purification begin to alter the inner field?

This is the first source in the queue that can become a manual of visionary discernment: veils, darkness, lights, colours, subtle centres, dhikr, altered perception, and the danger of confusing any passing image with realization.

3. Master structural reading

Read Kubrā through two linked lenses:

Lens 1 — Wayfaring as removal of veils

Al-Islam.org says Adab al-Sulūk concerns the journey toward God through removal of “the veils of negligence” and “the veils of distance and darkness.” It also distinguishes inward esoteric wayfaring from outward travel.

So the basic structure is:

ordinary negligence
veils of darkness
disciplined wayfaring
remembrance / dhikr
purification of perception
unveiling of lights
discernment of states
arrival / nearness
Lens 2 — Visionary perception as diagnosable phenomenon

Kubrā is not merely saying “visions happen.” The Kubrawī tradition develops a science of inner phenomena: colour, light, dream, image, subtle centres, and spiritual perception. A public summary states that Kubrā’s works discuss dreams and visions, degrees of luminous epiphany, images that occupy the mystic’s attention, and the interrelations of subtle centres.

This makes him essential for Imaginarium because he gives a phenomenological bridge between:

practice → perception → colour/light → subtle organ → spiritual diagnosis

