Source 8: al-Niffarī — Kitāb al-Mawāqif and Kitāb al-Mukhāṭabāt
1. Source identity

Primary source: Muḥammad ibn ʿAbd al-Jabbār al-Niffarī, Kitāb al-Mawāqif / The Book of Spiritual Standings or Stayings, and Kitāb al-Mukhāṭabāt / The Book of Divine Addresses.

Best-known English edition: A. J. Arberry, The Mawāqif and Mukhaṭabāt of Muḥammad ibn ʿAbdi’l-Jabbār al-Niffarī, first published in 1935 by Gibb Memorial Trust / Luzac. WorldCat lists the 1935 edition as edited with translation, commentary, and indices by Arberry.

Chisholme also identifies Arberry’s translation as the best-known English version. Public-access situation: Full scans and transcriptions circulate online, but many are hosted on unstable or copyright-unclear sites. Use extensive summation, table-of-contents mapping, short excerpts only, and public scholarly summaries. A Scribd preview gives a useful contents list for many Mawāqif, but do not rely on it for long quotation.

Text type: apophatic mystical address; fragmentary divine speech; Sufi “standing” text; non-systematic visionary theology.

Extraction mode:
Use structural summation and section-location mapping. This is not a quote-mining source. It is a source for stance, voice, apophasis, bewilderment, and the terrifying intimacy of divine address.

2. Why this source comes eighth

The sequence so far built:

Earlier source	Core gift
Avicenna / Corbin	Angel-guide, Orient/Occident, visionary recital
Suhrawardī	Light ontology and presential knowledge
Ibn ʿArabī, Fuṣūṣ	Divine names, prophetic manifestation
ʿAṭṭār	Bird-soul typology and annihilating journey
Ibn ʿArabī, Futūḥāt	Barzakh, dreams, body of light, spiritual practice
Rūzbihān	Ecstatic first-person visionary testimony
Kubrā	Disciplined visionary phenomenology, dhikr, colours, subtle centres

al-Niffarī now adds the missing apophatic address:

not journey, not system, not beauty, not light-phenomenology — but being made to stand before the Real until speech, knowledge, selfhood, and spiritual confidence are broken.

This is where Imaginarium gets its strongest source for bewilderment, non-conceptual encounter, divine speech, and the limits of mystical language.

3. Master structural reading

Read al-Niffarī as a text of arrested encounter.

The recurring formula is:

“He made me stand…”

The divine does not merely reveal information. It stations the servant before a truth, a sea, a veil, a light, a command, a silence, a bewilderment.

A recent scholarly article describes the Kitāb al-Mawāqif as a tenth-century Sufi text where fanāʾ means speaking from a kind of “non-perspective,” a theological paradox that Sufi literature handles creatively.

Another scholarly summary notes that al-Niffarī’s works are marked by direct dialogue between God and the mystic, where divine definitions of Sufi and Islamic values are transmitted through the mystic.

So the text’s basic engine is:

standing — the servant is halted.
address — God speaks.
unmaking — concepts fail.
bewilderment — the servant cannot resolve the encounter.
gnosis beyond possession — knowledge becomes exposure, not control.
return to speech — the text records what cannot really be contained in speech.
