Source 9: Jalāl al-Dīn Rūmī — selected Masnavī-yi Maʿnavī
1. Source identity

Primary source: Jalāl al-Dīn Rūmī, Masnavī-yi Maʿnavī, usually translated as The Masnavi, Mathnawi, or Spiritual Couplets.

Best public-access base: R. A. Nicholson’s classic translation and edition is available in public scans through Internet Archive; Vol. 2 is explicitly marked “Out_of_copyright” by its archive metadata.

Wikisource also hosts Whinfield’s public-domain abridged Masnavi I Ma’navi.

Copyright caution: Modern translations, including Oxford / Penguin / popular poetic versions, are copyrighted. Use Nicholson or Whinfield for public-domain passage work; use modern scholarship for structure only.

Text type: didactic Sufi poetic epic; parable-chain; anti-literalist imaginal pedagogy; prophetic-animal-human story machine.

Extraction mode:
Use focused public-domain passage packs, not the whole six-book ocean. The Masnavī is huge: public summaries describe it as six books, roughly 25,000 verses / 50,000 lines.

2. Why this source comes ninth

The previous sources gave doctrine, light, barzakh, visionary autobiography, colour-phenomenology, and apophatic address. Rūmī gives the missing teaching machine.

His contribution is:

The parable itself becomes an imaginal method.
A donkey, parrot, merchant, reed, prophet, king, slave-girl, lion, fox, chickpea, elephant, or candle can suddenly become the whole cosmos teaching itself.

The Masnavī is not systematic like Ibn ʿArabī, not architecturally concentrated like ʿAṭṭār, and not apophatically naked like al-Niffarī. It is a living field of stories, interruptions, reversals, jokes, Qurʾānic echoes, animals, prophets, tradesmen, fools, saints, and sudden mystical eruptions.

3. Master structural reading

The Masnavī should be treated as anti-literal pedagogy.

Its basic rhythm:

A story begins plainly.
Characters act from ordinary motives.
Rūmī interrupts himself.
The story opens into Qurʾān, hadith, animal speech, psychology, cosmology, or love.
The literal surface breaks.
The reader is forced to reread the scene symbolically.
The narrative may never “close” in ordinary terms.

Public summaries note that the Masnavī has no single framed plot and uses many voices: authorial teaching, storytelling, analogy, dialogue, moral reflection, spiritual discourse, and sudden hiatus.

So the companion should not map every story. It should build high-yield parable clusters.

4. Six-book map
Book	Function for Imaginarium
Book I	Opening reed, separation, longing, king/slave-girl, merchant/parrot, lion/hare: foundational pedagogy of desire, loss, cunning, image, and release.
Book II	Deeper moral psychology: ego tricks, prophetic lessons, animal fables, reversal of worldly intelligence.
Book III	Knowledge, Moses material, teacher-student reversals, limits of reason.
Book IV	More advanced spiritual psychology: form/meaning, hidden wisdom, reversals of status.
Book V	Law/path/truth relation; public scanned text says Book V begins by comparing religious law to a candle showing the way.
Book VI	Late synthesis, unfinished movement, final teaching intensification.
A public summary notes that the six books are often grouped in pairs: Books I–II around the lower self and self-deception; Books III–IV around reason and knowledge; Books V–VI around denying merely physical existence to understand God’s existence.
