Source 10: Maḥmūd Shabistarī — Gulshan-i Rāz / The Secret Rose Garden
1. Source identity

Primary source: Maḥmūd Shabistarī, Gulshan-i Rāz, usually translated as The Secret Rose Garden or The Mystic Rose Garden.

Core public editions:

Edition	Use
E. H. Whinfield, Gulshan i Raz: The Mystic Rose Garden, 1880	Best source because it includes Persian text, English translation, and notes chiefly from Muḥammad Lahījī’s commentary. Internet Archive has a scan.
Florence Lederer, The Secret Rose Garden, 1920
Public-domain poetic rendering; good for readable passages. Sacred Texts hosts it and says the poem was written as a reply to questions from a Sufi doctor of Herat.
Matheson Trust PDF of Whinfield
Useful public PDF, with Lahījī-based notes and Whinfield’s apparatus.
Copyright caution: Whinfield 1880 and Lederer 1920 are public-domain working bases. Avoid relying on modern Red Wheel/Weiser editions, which Google Books marks as copyright.

Text type: compact Persian Sufi metaphysical poem; question-answer treatise; symbol-compression manual.

Extraction mode: Use Whinfield/Lederer for public-domain passage packs, Lahījī notes for commentary, and summaries for structure.

2. Why this source comes tenth

After Rūmī’s sprawling parable-field, Shabistarī gives the opposite mode:

compressed metaphysical poetry.

This is the project’s best source for:

point and circle imagery
face, hair, mole, wine, idol, temple
human form as mirror
divine manifestation
symbolic condensation
question-answer metaphysics
poetic theology as diagram

The poem was completed around 1317 and is described by the Borges Center as one of the most important philosophical poems in Persian. It also notes that more than thirty commentaries exist, with Lahījī’s commentary the best known and the basis of Whinfield’s English version.

3. Master structural reading

Read Gulshan-i Rāz as a compressed Sufi metaphysical catechism.

It is not a narrative like ʿAṭṭār, not a parable ocean like Rūmī, not a visionary diary like Rūzbihān. It is a series of answers to doctrinal-symbolic questions.

Its engine:

A question is asked.
Shabistarī answers through compact metaphysical verse.
Ordinary religious/philosophical terms are re-read symbolically.
Human form, cosmos, beauty, wine, idol, and lover become metaphysical diagrams.
Lahījī’s commentary expands the compressed poem into a Sufi metaphysical system.
