Source 14: Sayyid Ḥaydar Āmulī — Jāmiʿ al-Asrār wa Manbaʿ al-Anwār / Inner Secrets of the Path
1. Source identity

Primary figure: Sayyid Ḥaydar Āmulī, 1319–c.1385, Shiʿi gnostic, philosopher, and major interpreter of Ibn ʿArabī.

Primary source cluster:

Jāmiʿ al-Asrār wa Manbaʿ al-Anwār — The Compendium of Mysteries and Source of Lights
Asrār al-Sharīʿa wa Aṭwār al-Ṭarīqa wa Anwār al-Ḥaqīqa — translated as Inner Secrets of the Path
Naṣṣ al-Nuṣūṣ fī Sharḥ Fuṣūṣ al-Ḥikam — Āmulī’s commentary on Ibn ʿArabī’s Fuṣūṣ

Best public-access base: Inner Secrets of the Path is freely available on Al-Islam.org and as a PDF through Sufism.ir. It is described as a work on how spiritual travellers should walk the path using the Sharia, and it deals with the roots and branches of religion.

Corbin link: Henry Corbin and Osman Yahia edited Āmulī’s La Philosophie Shîʿite, a major edition connected to Āmulī’s Shiʿi metaphysics. A Cambridge review identifies the 1969 Corbin/Yahia edition as Sayyed Haydar Amoli, La Philosophie Shîʿite.

Copyright caution: Inner Secrets is publicly readable, but modern translation status should still be treated cautiously. Use summation and short excerpts. For Jāmiʿ al-Asrār, access is more scattered, so use public articles, bibliographic records, and source-traceable paraphrase.

2. Why this source comes fourteenth

After Mullā Ṣadrā, the next strongest source is Āmulī because he fuses:

Ibn ʿArabī’s metaphysics + Shiʿi walāya + esoteric interpretation + law/path/truth architecture.

This is the missing Corbinian Shiʿi bridge. Āmulī is not just another Akbarian metaphysician. He asks:

What if the deepest Sufi metaphysics and the inner meaning of Shiʿism are the same reality viewed under different names?

Public summaries describe his project as a synthesis of Shiʿism and Sufism, especially through the framework of sharīʿa, ṭarīqa, ḥaqīqa and the role of the Imams as bearers of mystical knowledge.

3. Master structural reading

Read Āmulī as a reconciliation engine.

His core structure:

Sharīʿa — outer law, form, body of religion.
Ṭarīqa — path, discipline, inward movement.
Ḥaqīqa — truth, unveiling, inner reality.
Walāya — sanctity / spiritual authority / esoteric guardianship.
Imamate — historical and metaphysical locus of walāya.
Tawḥīd — unity read through both Akbarian and Shiʿi lenses.
Taʾwīl — symbols, law, scripture, and doctrine opened inwardly.

Al-Islam’s description of Inner Secrets says it discusses how spiritual travellers walk the path through the Sharia and deals with roots and branches of religion. Google Books also describes it as integrating inner and outer aspects of Islam through levels of meaning.

