Source 15: ʿAlāʾ al-Dawla Simnānī — Kubrawī Subtle Centres, Colour-Vision, and Critique of Ibn ʿArabī
1. Source identity

Primary figure: ʿAlāʾ al-Dawla Simnānī, 1261–1336, Persian Kubrawī Sufi master, poet, mystic, and critic of Ibn ʿArabī’s growing influence in Iran. Encyclopaedia Iranica identifies him as a major Ilkhanid-period mystic and notes his opposition to Ibn ʿArabī’s influence.

Primary source cluster:

Simnānī’s Kubrawī subtle-centre writings — especially his system of inner centres, colours, and prophetic correspondences.
Anti-Akbarian polemical material — especially his critique of Ibn ʿArabī’s language around absolute being and identity.
Kubrawī colour-vision lineage — extending Najm al-Dīn Kubrā’s visionary light phenomenology into a more articulated subtle-body map.

Public access: clean full English editions are limited. Use Encyclopaedia Iranica, Hurqalya, public scholarly articles, article abstracts, and cautious summaries. Hurqalya identifies Simnānī as a Kubrawī mystic who modified Ibn ʿArabī’s concept of waḥdat al-wujūd and became influential for later Naqshbandīs.

Copyright caution: use extensive summation. Avoid long quotation. Treat online PDFs and scans case-by-case.

2. Why this source comes fifteenth

After Āmulī, who Shiʿized and reconciled Akbarian metaphysics, Simnānī is the necessary counter-current.

He adds:

a disciplined subtle-body colour map and a critique of excessive identity-language in Ibn ʿArabī.

This gives Imaginarium a vital balancing source:

not just “all is manifestation”
not just “visionary lights appear”
but which inner organ is seeing, what colour marks the state, and where metaphysical language risks collapsing God and world too quickly
3. Master structural reading

Read Simnānī as a corrective Kubrawī cartographer.

His engine:

The human being contains subtle centres.
Each centre has a colour, state, prophetic resonance, and stage of purification.
Visionary colours are diagnostic, not decorative.
Spiritual ascent is not abstract unity-talk; it passes through embodied inner organs.
Ibn ʿArabī’s metaphysics must be handled carefully so unity does not become careless identity.

A PhilPapers abstract says Simnānī’s critique of Ibn ʿArabī centres on two issues: using wujūd al-muṭlaq for God, and a phrase from the Futūḥāt about God manifesting things while being their very entity.

