# Coverage-First Source Companion Blueprint

## Source 17: Fakhr al-Dīn ʿIrāqī — *Lamaʿāt / Divine Flashes*

## 1. Source identity

**Primary source:** Fakhr al-Dīn ʿIrāqī, *Lamaʿāt*, translated as *Divine Flashes*.

**Why this is next:** after Jāmī’s *Lawāʾiḥ*, ʿIrāqī is the obvious companion source: Jāmī’s *Lawāʾiḥ* was written “in the same strain” as ʿIrāqī’s *Lamaʿāt*, and ʿIrāqī’s work itself emerges from the meeting of Persian love-mysticism with Qūnawī’s Akbarian reading of Ibn ʿArabī. ([Poetry Chaikhana][1])

**Public access / edition:** the best-known English translation is William Chittick and Peter Lamborn Wilson, *Fakhruddin Iraqi: Divine Flashes*, Paulist Press, 1982. It is copyrighted, so use sparingly. Google Books lists the edition, translators, publisher, date, and length. ([Google Books][2])

**Public-source situation:** no clean public-domain English translation is readily available. Public summaries and excerpts exist, but use them as support only. The Persian *Divan* is public-domain marked on Internet Archive, but it is not the same as a full public English *Lamaʿāt*. ([Internet Archive][3])

**Text type:** Persian Sufi love-metaphysics; mixed prose and poetry; Akbarian love ontology; “flash” literature.

**Extraction mode:** extensive summation, flash-by-flash architecture, short legally safe excerpts only.

---

# 2. Master structural reading

Read *Lamaʿāt* as **Ibn ʿArabī through the language of Love**.

Its core synthesis:

> Aḥmad Ghazālī gives the language of lover, beloved, and love.
> Qūnawī gives the Akbarian metaphysical skeleton.
> ʿIrāqī makes Love the name of the Real’s self-disclosure.

Public summaries state that *Lamaʿāt* combines Ibn ʿArabī’s philosophy with Persian love-mysticism, and that it was encouraged by Aḥmad Ghazālī’s *Sawāniḥ al-ʿUshshāq*. ([Wikipedia][4])

---

# 3. Part / function map

The work is usually described as **27 or 28 flashes**; one source notes that early texts suggest one chapter may have been divided, producing the 27/28 uncertainty. ([Wikipedia][4])

| Unit                    | Function                                                              |
| ----------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Opening flashes         | Establish Love as primordial reality.                                 |
| Lover / Beloved flashes | Split of subject/object inside Love’s self-display.                   |
| Mirror flashes          | Forms as reflective surfaces of the One.                              |
| Veil flashes            | Manifestation both reveals and hides.                                 |
| Union flashes           | Lover and Beloved collapse without flattening difference.             |
| Poetry interludes       | Doctrine becomes intoxicated speech.                                  |
| Later flashes           | Love as annihilation, bewilderment, and total identity-in-difference. |

